        <body>       
                
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#91;&#63;&#93; 15<lb/>
                Nissan 30 5647<lb/></p>
            <p>Boston.<lb/>
                Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Morais<lb/>
                My very dear friend<lb/></p>
            <p>I am in receipt of<lb/> yours with enclosed copy<lb/> of eulogy which the Boston<lb/> <sic>Traveller</sic> published &#38; should<lb/> have replied but press of<lb/> extreme important business<lb/> prevented my so doing I<lb/> received a most beautiful<lb/> letter from my friend the<lb/> pret&#91;&#63;&#93; whither He writes<lb/> as follows &#34;I thank thee<lb/> for the <sic>priviledge</sic> of reading<lb/> the tender &#38; beautiful<lb/> <del>article</del> tribute of Dr. Morais<lb/> to thy beloved wife I could<lb/> not help thinking as I read<lb/> of her lovely life if <del>godness</del><lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>goodness deed charity<lb/> <del>Rearing</del> that her leaving is a precious<lb/> legacy and that to have<lb/> had the love and<lb/> companionship of such<lb/> a woman must be a<lb/> cause of thankfulness<lb/> to our father in Heaven<lb/> as a blessing beyond all<lb/> price<lb/></p>
            <p>But what could be<lb/> added to the touching<lb/> eulogy of Morais<lb/> I am <del>ty</del> truly thy friend<lb/> John G. Whitten&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>If you so desire perhaps<lb/> you will kindly send<lb/> the extract to the Jewish<lb/> <del>Exponed</del> Exponent the<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>papers are so anxious to get anything<lb/> which come from Mr. Whitten pen<lb/> &#38; I want to do all I possibly can<lb/> to assist the newcomer more<lb/> especially as your son is one of the<lb/> Editors<lb/></p>
            <p>Altho my daughter &#38; son grief is<lb/> beyond the usual for their deep &#38;<lb/> undeniable loss I pray to God to<lb/> assist us all through this dreadful<lb/> ordeal.<lb/></p>
            <p>I do hope when you write as often<lb/> as you can you will excuse me<lb/> if I am not so prompt in answering<lb/> The impression of your sermon has<lb/> had a most beneficial effect to our<lb/> race &#38; its publication in the leading<lb/> paper the <sic>Traveller</sic> has been extraordinary<lb/> some of the best leading mrechants &#38; my<lb/> friends have cut out the article &#38; spoken<lb/> to me of your immense talent.  I should be<lb/> so glad if you could come to Boston at some<lb/> future&#44; with sincere regards to all your family I am<lb/> yours very truly Alfred A Marcus<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Do you require any copies of the <sic>Traveller</sic> I shall be glad to<lb/> send as many as you require<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
